The '''Coin of the Year Award''' ('''COTY''') is an awards program founded and annually conducted by the American publisher [[Krause Publications]] of Iola, Wisconsin, and directed at the coin producing industry.<ref>{{cite book|title=The American Legion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PLEMAQAAMAAJ|year=1986|publisher=American Legion|page=13}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EkpmAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Coin+of+the+Year+award%22+Krause+Publications&dq=%22Coin+of+the+Year+award%22+Krause+Publications&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5AHtUu_INcqiyAHYpoHAAQ&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAA The Numismatist, Volume 113 ] American Numismatic Association, 2000</ref> Awards are given for numismatic design, artistic vision and craftsmanship. A panel of international judges chooses the coins from those issued two years prior to the year of the award.<ref name=glow>[http://www.bayview-news.com/?s=coin+of+the+year "Glow-in-the dark quarter is coin of the year"]. ''Bayview News'', November 20, 2013</ref>
==History==
The COTY was awarded for the first time in 1984, when coins issued in 1982 were assessed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.numismaster.com/ta/inside_numis.jsp?page=coin-of-the-year-archive |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-10-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909122212/http://www.numismaster.com/ta/inside_numis.jsp?page=coin-of-the-year-archive |archivedate=2014-09-09 |df= }}. List of the COTY Awards since 1984. In 2015 this list was also published as a paper-printed book: Donald Scarinci: Coin of the Year. Celebrating Three Decades of the Best in Coin Design and Craftsmanship, Krause Publications, Iola (WI) 2015.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=vW95H-X295AC&pg=PA36&dq=Coin+of+the+Year++award+Krause+Publications&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IgHtUui2ConkyAG044GACQ&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Coin%20of%20the%20Year%20%20award%20Krause%20Publications&f=false Watercraft on World Coins: America and Asia, 1800-2008] By Yossi Dotan</ref>
==Categories== Awards are given in ten categories, and three coins are selected in each category: *Most Historically Significant: Coins which commemorate events, institutions, physical entities, or individual which are deemed to be most important in terms of the historical heritage of a people or mankind. *Best Contemporary Event: Coins which commemorate events, institutions physical entities, or individuals which are deemed to be most important in terms of current or recent events influencing a people or mankind. *Best Gold: Coins fabricated of GOLD, Platinum, Palladium, or another exotic precious metal which have all-around aesthetic and commercial appeal. *Best Silver: Coins fabricated of silver which have all-around aesthetic and commercial appeal. *Best Crown: Coins which have all-around aesthetic and commercial appeal, and have a minimum diameter of 33mm.. *Best Trade Circulating monetary unit coins which are made of non-precious metals, possess all-around aesthetic and commercial appeal. *Most Popular: Coins with commercial sales and artistic caliber which appeals to the international general public. *Most Artistic: Coins selected solely on the value of their artistic merit. *Most Innovative Coinage Concept: Coins which contain pioneering metallic alloys, non-typical coinage materials, planchet shapes, thickness, sizes, themes, distribution methods or other innovations.<ref name=glow /> *Most Inspirational Coin: Coins featuring themes, events, institutions, physical entities, or individuals that represent peace, freedom, and human rights.
